3. (2 pt) Formally test if prices are the same in each borough. Choose an appropriate test, run it, and present the results in a way accessible to an investor with little statistical background.

#Null hypothesis : the price is same in all boroughs (no-difference)

#As there are multiple observations to compare - we will use the ANOVA to test this. 
q3 <-  airbnb_price %>% separate("nbhood_full", into = c("Neigbourhoods", NA ), sep = ",") %>% separate("price", into = c ("price", NA ), sep = " ") %>% mutate (price = as.numeric (price))
## Warning: Expected 2 pieces. Additional pieces discarded in 1 rows [21983].
test <- oneway.test(price ~ Neigbourhoods , data = q3,   var.equal = FALSE)
q3
test
## 
##  One-way analysis of means (not assuming equal variances)
## 
## data:  price and Neigbourhoods
## F = 545.79, num df = 4.0, denom df = 1671.3, p-value < 2.2e-16

P value (which is much lesser than 0.05) suggests that we can reject the null hypothesis stating that the price is same in all boroughs, however we observe there is significant difference in the prices between the boroughs.

The one-way test actually tells us that there is a significant difference in prices between at-least one pair of boroughs, but we do-not know which pair is that, hence we conduct a post-hoc test to see if there is a significant difference between other pairs as well!

4. (2 pt) Conduct a post-hoc test to determine which is/are the borough(s) with the highest price. Which are the borough(s) with the lowest price?

question2p2

pairwise.t.test(q3$price, q3$Neigbourhoods, p.adjust = "bonf")

Manhattan has the highest price and a significant difference in price from all other boroughs. We can see that Manhattan has a significantly different price from other boroughs as well as the p-value is less than 0.005.

The average price for rental is lowest in Bronx, and the price is not significantly different from all other boroughs. The price is not significantly different than Staten Island and Queens

5. (1 pt) Examine the room types. What is the frequency of each rental type in each borough? Prepare a graph illustrating it.

library(readxl)
airbnb_room_type <- read_excel("airbnb_room_type.xlsx")
View(airbnb_room_type)

neighbourhoods <- airbnb_price %>% separate("nbhood_full", into = c("boroughs", NA ), sep = ",")
## Warning: Expected 2 pieces. Additional pieces discarded in 1 rows [21983].
joineddata <- inner_join(airbnb_room_type ,neighbourhoods, by = "listing_id")
q5data <- joineddata  %>% mutate(room_type = tolower(room_type))
q5data %>% 
  group_by(boroughs, room_type) %>% 
  summarize(n = n()) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = boroughs, y = n, fill = room_type)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  geom_text(aes(label = n), position = position_dodge(0.9), vjust = -0.5) + 
  scale_fill_viridis_d() + 
  theme_classic()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'boroughs'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

This graph illustrates the types of room types in each borough, as well the number of each type of room types in each borough.

6. (2 pt) Do boroughs differ in what room types are the most common? Formally test it.

For this question we conduct a chi-square test as there are categorical variables that we need to test. Chi-square null hypothesis : There is no relation between boroughs and room types.

neighbourhoods <- airbnb_price %>% separate("nbhood_full", into = c("boroughs", NA ), sep = ",")
## Warning: Expected 2 pieces. Additional pieces discarded in 1 rows [21983].
joineddata<- inner_join(airbnb_room_type ,neighbourhoods, by = "listing_id")
q6 <- joineddata %>% mutate(room_type = tolower(room_type)) %>% group_by( boroughs, room_type) %>% count() %>% group_by(boroughs)%>% mutate(percentcommon = n/sum(n)*100 ) %>% group_by(boroughs) %>% filter (percentcommon == max (percentcommon))
q6 
chisq_test(x = q5data, room_type ~ boroughs)

The p-value less than 0.05, that means that the room-types in each borough are significantly different. This also means that the most common room types in each borough differed significantly from each other.
